When you buy a new computer, it's usually a new computer with a new hard drive and new memory. The hard drive is where all your files live, and it's not meant to last forever. When you buy a new computer, it's also a new computer with a new processor. The processor is where all your calculations live, and it's not meant to last forever. So the computer is basically just a bunch of parts that work together to do your work. Each part has its own expiration date, so if one of them stops working, the computer stops working. response: Ockham 's / Occam 's Razor is the law of the least explanation. It says that when you have two theories that explain the same thing, the one with the fewest explanations is the best. So if you have two theories about something and they both explain the same thing, the theory that has the least number of things that need to be true to make it work is the best. In short, it means that if you have two theories that explain the same thing, pick the one with the fewest assumptions. I think that is the best way to describe it.

question: Zeno 's Paradox , The Grandfather Paradox , Searle 's Chinese Room , Hilbert 's Hotel , Einstein 's Twin Paradox and Schrodinger 's Cat all explained like you 're 5 ( YouTube link ) Youtube link : URL_0 Explain like I'm five.
response: Zeno's paradox: Zeno of Elea was a Greek philosopher who lived in the 5th century BC. He was one of the first people to come up with some very strange ideas about time and space. One of his most famous ideas is called the Dichotomy paradox. It goes something like this: A man wants to walk from his house to the store. As he walks, he reaches the halfway point between his house and the store. At that point, he has to walk half way again to get to the other halfway point. He does this again and again. He keeps walking half way again and again. He never gets anywhere because he can never reach the store. The Grandfather Paradox: The grandfather paradox is a hypothetical situation where someone travels back in time and kills their own grandfather before their father was born. This would mean that the person would never have been born, so they could not have gone back in time and killed their grandfather. It is a paradox because it creates a contradiction. Searle's Chinese Room: In 1980, John Searle published an article called "Minds, Brains and Programs" in which he argued against the idea that computers can think. He said that if you put a person into a room with a bunch of Chinese symbols and instructions on how to manipulate them, the person would not be able to understand what the computer was doing, even though the computer was manipulating the symbols just as the person was.
